			<title>Nvidia throws its hat into the portable console ring - sortof</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?74613-Nvidia-throws-its-hat-into-the-portable-console-ring-sortof&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 07 Jan 2013 20:38:28 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[CES is coming up this week, I believe, and one of the first cool new things I've seen people talking about is Nvidia's new handheld gaming device. http://shield.nvidia.com/ 
 
It looks like a standard dual stick console controller with a small screen attached. It comes with android installed, but I...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>CES is coming up this week, I believe, and one of the first cool new things I've seen people talking about is Nvidia's new handheld gaming device. <a href="http://shield.nvidia.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://shield.nvidia.com/</a><br />
<br />
It looks like a standard dual stick console controller with a small screen attached. It comes with android installed, but I think it's primary intent is going to be to stream games from a gaming PC, essentially taking your PC with you wherever you go. Steam and their new &quot;Big Picture mode&quot; is mentioned specifically, and I wonder if this is the project Valve has not been talking about.<br />
<br />
It bears a resemblance to OnLive, which was a great idea that sort of petered out for various reasons. The tech geeks on the forum I saw this on seem to be excited about Nvidia's streaming solution, but I know absolutely nothing about it.<br />
<br />
As cool and daring as this is, I have to wonder if there is a market for such a device. If you want a portable gaming machine you are likely to get one with exclusive games, if you hate consoles and only play on PCs, you probably aren't going to want to give up keyboard and mouse for a gamepad.<br />
<br />
So I know there are a lot of you that don't like portables, or only play games on the PC. Would this interest you? What would your pricepoint be? <br />
<br />
I can't see paying more than $100 myself, but doubt it will go lower than $200, possibly more. And there is the one small caveat that you need a kepler based gpu to host the games on in the first place (kepler is their newest line, the 660s or whatever).</div>

]]></content:encoded>
